"Almost right away after the stem cells are infused into your body, theyll travel through your bloodstream to your bone marrow. Theyll start to divide and create healthy new blood cells. Engraftment is when your body accepts the transplant and your blood cell counts start to recover." Source
GVHD can occur after allogenic haemotopoietic cell transplantation or with solid organs containing lymphoid tissue. (Bowel transplant was one example)
GVHD arises when immune cells transplanted from a non-identical donor (graft) into the recipient (host), recognize the host cells as "foreign," thereby initiating a graft-versus-host reaction.

Involves skin and mucous membranes, GI tract and liver, Lungs.
2. and the transfer of immuno competent T lymphocytes from an HLA non-identical donor
3. The host must have antigens that are lacking in the donor cells which cause the donor cells to recognize the host cells as 'foreign'.

  • Acute GVHD (aGVHD) Characterized by a rapid onset and acute disease course. Occurs within 100 days of the transplant.

    • [!TIP] Mnemonic: G.V.H.D
      G for gut - enteritis, V - ? H - hepatitis, D - dermtitis

  • Chronic GVHD (cGVHD) Characterized by a chronic disease course that can involve virtually all organs with variable manifestations, including sclerosis;

Graft Vs. Leukemia effect

#2021BSQ-JUL Q05

[!INFO] A kind of useful GVHD
Since donor cells tend to kill residual leukaemia cells, allogenic stem cell transplant is associated with reduced rate of recurrent of leukemia.

Allogeneic hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (allo-SCT) is the most established and commonly used cellular immunotherapy in cancer care. It is the most potent anti-leukemic therapy in patients with acute myeloid leukemia (AML) and is routinely used with curative intent in patients with intermediate and poor risk disease. Donor T cells, and possibly other immune cells, eliminate residual leukemia cells after prior (radio)chemotherapy. This immune-mediated response is known as graft-versus-leukemia (GvL) - Source

Effective renal plasma flow can be calculated using the Fick principle with para-amino hippuric acid. This is a substance that is filtered and secreted by the kidney (but not reabsorbed) meaning that almost all of it is removed in a pass through the kidney. (extraction ratio is aroun 90%).
This yields a normal renal plasma flow of 625 ml/min.

[!TIP] That's one tasty 625 ml

Normal GFR = 125 ml / Min.

GFR is the volume of ultrafiltrate formed each minute.

#2021BSQ-JUL Q10
Ideally, clearance should be measured using a substance which is freely filtered, not secreted and not reabsorbed. The ideal substance is inulin.
For such a substance, clearance would be equal to the GFR.

#2021BSQ-JUL Q10
See this: Source

Regulation of renal blood flow:

  • Noradrenaline - decreases renal blood flow.
  • Dopamine - increases renal blood flow.
  • Angiotensin - Efferent > afferent constriction
  • Prostaglandins -> increase blood flow in the cortex.
  • Acetylcholine - renal vasodilation
  • High protein diet -> increases renal blood flow.
  • Adrenaline -> increased resistance and decreased renal blood flow.
  • Atrial and brain natriuretic peptide (ANP and BNP) decrease arteriolar resistance and increase renal blood flow Source

Cell injury

  • Note that cellular malfunction precedes cell death. (i.e they don't have to die to stop working properly).
  • Visible changes (even at EM level) only occur after cell 'death'.

Overview of cell injury

vasoactive amines

Preformed mediators released from cells very quickly in reponse to inflmmation.

  • Histamine
    • Stored in platelets, mainly mast cells, basophils
    • release triggered by physical damage, IgE crosslinking,
    • C3a and C5a - anaphylatoxins
    • Neuropeptides - Substance P
    • Cytokines like IL-1 and IL-8
    • leukocyte derived histamine releasing proteins.
      Serotonin
  • Biochemistry: [[adrenalineSynthesisMonoamines.jpg]]
  • Preformed mediator released from platelet granules during platelet aggregation.
  • Causes vasocontriction
  • Also a neurotransmitter.

It's interesting to note that histamine and serotonin are both involved in nausea and emesis as their blockers are used as antiemetics.

Source- NICE Guidelines

What is stable angina?

Angina is arbitrarily defined as stable when the angina episodes are stable over a period of 36 months.
Angina equivalents: Exertional SOB in absence of lung disease, extreme exertional fatigue; commoner in women, elderly and diabetes patients.
Source

Mortality is 2 - 3% per year.

  1. Relieve symptoms
    1. Measures to treat an anginal episode
    2. Measure to prevent angina recurrences[[#antianginal medications]]
  2. Preventing disease progression
    • Medication - aspirin, newer guidelines recommend ACEi as well (particular if patient has DM) Source
    • Risk factor management - lipid lowering therapy - statins, smoking cessation, BP control, weight loss, optimal DM management, regular exercise, stress reduction etc.
  3. Prevent future cardiac events (like ACS, death)

Treating angina episodes

Short acting nitrate is the drug of choice.
Mechanism: GTN causes coronary artery dilation and improves coronary blood flow. (but too much dilation will decrease blood pressure in vessels)

Repeat dose - 5 minutes.
If pain doesn't settle 5 minutes after the second dose, call ambulance.

There are 5 main groups of antianginal drugs.
1 and 2 are first line.
Others are second line.
See the numbered list below.

  • Firt line anti anginals: BB and CCB. They can be alternated or combined.

  • Second line antianginals:: Long acting nitrates, ivabradine, nicorandil, ranolazine

    1. First line anti anginal medications; Initial step in angina management is "beta blocker montherapy." Beta blockers are the only antianginals proven to reduce reinfarction and reduce mortablity.

    2. Mechanism: reduce heart rate and contractility -> reduced oxygen demand -> therefore delay the onset of angina during exercise. Also reduced LV wall stress by their antihypertensive action.

    3. Beta blockers reduce mortality when it comes to secondary prevention but technically, there is no evidence that they prevent the first MI in a patient with angina.

    4. contraindicated in LV dysfunction.

    5. Non-dyhydropyridine CCB and BB combination should be avoided due to risk of bradycardia and atrioventricular block.Source

      1. Mnemonic: Non-DHP = Nodal => conduction effects (? do they actually act on the nodes? #TODO)

These second line antianginals are used only when

  • The patient cannot tolerate one or both of the above drugs. If only one of the above isn't tolerated, add the 2nd line drug in combination.
  • If the patient's angina isn't controlled on two first line anti-anginals, they are a candidate for revascularization. While they are waiting for revascularization, a second line antianginal can be added. (or if revascularization isn't an option)

Options:

  • Long acting nitrate

  • Ivabradine

  • Nicorandil

  • ranolazine

    1. Mechanism: They dilate systemic arteries, systemic veins and coronary arteries.
      Venodilation >> arterial dilation. (increased bioavailability to venous smooth muscle)
      Therefore, the main antianginal effect is due to venodilation -> reduced preload -> reduced ventricular wall stress -> reduced oxygen demand -> antianginal effect.
  1. Ranolazine: Newer addition - late sodium channel blocker.
    1. inhibits late sodium current and hence indirectly reduces intracellular calcium and force of contraction,without affecting heart rate;
    2. Why too much intracellular calcium is bad: (TLDR;)

      1. Intracellular calcium overload is believed to be critical to the mechanism of decreased left ventricular relaxation caused by ischemia and reperfusion. Elevated left ventricular diastolic wall tension compromises myocardial blood flow even further. Additionally, calcium overload has adverse effects on myocardial electrical activity predisposing to ventricular tachycardia Source

  2. Ivabradin can be used as an antianginal.

Source

  • Probably no mortality benefit. Source
  1. Niconrandil: Potassium channel activator (K-ATP channel).
    1. Potassium channel activators dilate arterial smooth muscle.
    2. Nicorandil has nitrate groups as well so it also dilates veins.
    3. So arterial and venodilation exerts an antianginal effect.

ACEi can be used to preventing ACS in aginal patients. Source

#2021BSQ-JUL Q05

Mnemonic : BPH - bradykning, prostaglandin and histamine act together.

  • Crucial role in inflammation.: 3 actions ->
    • HVasodilation -> increases blood flow
    • permeability -> oedema
    • sensitization of nociceptors -> pain
  • A product of the kinin cascade. A poorly understood enzyme cascade in plasma, like the clotting cascade and complement cascade.
  • Increases capillary permeability acting alongside histamine and prostaglandin;
  • potent vasodilator. -> accumulation causes angiooedema and possibly the dry cough of ACEi therapy.
  • Broken down by ACE and neprilysin.

Hereditary angiooedema

#autosomalDominant
C1 esterase deficiency.
Episodes of angiooedema not responding to histamines or adrenaline, usually after a flu like prodrome.
No urticaria.
C1 esterase is a complement activation inhibitor.
Defieciency of C1 esterase causes unchecked activation of C1, C2 and C4.
This causes activation of kallikrein which causes increased production of bradykinin --> angiooedema.
Low C2 and C4 levels are seen in hereditary angioedema.
Treatment: plasma derived C1 inhibitor.

Mirtazapine - blocks presynaptic alpha receptors (increasing serotonin secretion) and post synaptic 5-HT2 and 5-HT3 recectors, leaving more serotonin for 5-HT1 receptors.
